\par \plain\f2\fs36\cf0\b\ul Introduction\plain\f2\fs36\cf3\b 
\par \pard\plain\f2\fs36\cf0 
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf0 \tab 
\par \tab Wally is a program for the manipulation of Quake II \plain\f2\fs20\cf1\ul .wal files\plain\f2\fs20\cf2 {\v Scribble20}\plain\f2\fs20\cf0 .  It currently allows you to:-
\par 
\par \tab - Load, view and save .wal files.
\par \tab - Create new textures.
\par \tab - Browse texture directories.
\par \tab - Set content and surface flags in textures.
\par \tab - Edit at a pixel level.
\par \tab - Add various effects, such as bullet holes, scratches, and so on.
\par \tab - Import and export PCX, BMP and Quake MIP files.
\par \tab - Change the palette of a texture.
\par \tab - Copy and paste to and from the Windows clipboard.
\par \tab - Resample individual mips within a texture, using ReMip Deluxe.
\par \tab - Drag-and-drop files into the Wally desktop.
\par 
\par \tab Wally was conceived in order to allow Quake2 editors to bring custom textures into their levels with the maximum of ease, by avoiding the need to convert images between formats in image editing apps and eliminating awkward DOS-prompt programs for the creation of the actual .wal file. It also allows flags to be set in the .wal files defining light levels, transparency and other properties of the texture. Wally is, and always will be, freeware.\plain\f2\fs20 

{\page}

