\deflang2057\pard\plain\f2\fs32\cf0\b .WAL Files:
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf0 Quake II, unlike Quake, stores all its textures inside its .pak files in the form
\par of .wal files - a .wal file consists of four images, each half the size of the
\par previous, in order to be able to map textures at different resolutions depending
\par on the distance of the viewer.  See the topic \plain\f2\fs20\cf2 #{\footnote # main}\plain\f2\fs20\cf1\strike Using .WAL Files\plain\f2\fs20\cf2 {\v Scribble30}\plain\f2\fs20\cf0  for more information
\par on the use of .WALs.\plain\f2\fs20 

