\deflang2057\pard\qc\plain\f2\fs32\cf0\b 
\par Set Flags
\par \pard\plain\f2\fs20\cf0 
\par \pard\qc\plain\f2\fs20\cf0 This is the Texture Information dialogue:
\par 
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf2 \{bmc texflag.bmp\}\plain\f2\fs20\cf0 
\par 
\par Use this to set content and surface properties of a texture - this will
\par give the properties you set to any brush with the texture, unless you change
\par the settings in your level editor.
\par 
\par \pard\plain\f2\fs20\cf0 The options available are as follows:
\par 
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf0\b Name\plain\f2\fs20\cf0  - allows you to specify an internal name for the texture; it is best if the name matches the filename - e.g, a custom texture in "\\baseq2\\textures\\mymod\\custom.wal" would be called "mymod/custom"
\par 
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf0\b Width \plain\f2\fs20\cf0 and\plain\f2\fs20\cf0\b  Height \plain\f2\fs20\cf0 - displays the dimensions of the texture.
\par 
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf0\b Next Animation Texture\plain\f2\fs20\cf0  - this allows you to specify a texture to follow the texture in an animation. Use the internal name of the texture, not the path to the file (i.e, "mymod/custom2" instead of "..\\textures\\mymod\\custom.wal").
\par 
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf0\b Value (light)\plain\f2\fs20\cf0  - when the 'light' flag is set, this number will be the intensity of the light given off by the texture.
\par 
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf0\b\ul Surface Property Flags:-
\par 
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf0 These flags affect only individual faces which have the texture.
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf0\b\ul 
\par \tab \plain\f2\fs20\cf0\b Light\plain\f2\fs20\cf0  - Sets the texture to emit light, which is coloured to match the texture in GL mode.
\par 
\par \tab \plain\f2\fs20\cf0\b Slick\plain\f2\fs20\cf0  - Sets the texture to act like ice.
\par 
\par \tab \plain\f2\fs20\cf0\b Sky\plain\f2\fs20\cf0  - Sets the texture to plot the sky set for the level instead of the image in the .wal.
\par 
\par \tab \plain\f2\fs20\cf0\b Warp\plain\f2\fs20\cf0  - Sets the texture to shift and swirl like water, lava, and so on.
\par 
\par \tab \plain\f2\fs20\cf0\b Trans33\plain\f2\fs20\cf0  and \plain\f2\fs20\cf0\b Trans66\plain\f2\fs20\cf0  - Sets the texture to be 33% or 66% translucent.
\par 
\par \tab \plain\f2\fs20\cf0\b Flowing\plain\f2\fs20\cf0  - Sets the texture to move. Used with rivers or conveyor belts.
\par 
\par \tab \plain\f2\fs20\cf0\b NoDraw\plain\f2\fs20\cf0  - The texture will not be drawn in the game.
\par 
\par \tab \plain\f2\fs20\cf0\b Hint\plain\f2\fs20\cf0  - The texture will be a hint brush. Do not use if you do not understand what these are :)
\par 
\par \tab \plain\f2\fs20\cf0\b Skip\plain\f2\fs20\cf0  - A face with this texture will be completely ignored by Q2.
\par 
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf0\b\ul Content Property Flags:-
\par 
\par \plain\f2\fs20\cf0 These flags affect the entire brush to which the texture is applied.
\par 
\par \tab \plain\f2\fs20\cf0\b Solid\plain\f2\fs20\cf0  - Default for all brushes.\plain\f2\fs20\cf0\b 
\par 
\par \tab Window\plain\f2\fs20\cf0  - Sets the brush to be a window.\plain\f2\fs20\cf0\b 
\par 
\par \tab Aux \plain\f2\fs20\cf0 - Not used\plain\f2\fs20\cf0\b 
\par 
\par \tab Lava\plain\f2\fs20\cf0  - The brush is lava.\plain\f2\fs20\cf0\b 
\par 
\par \tab Slime\plain\f2\fs20\cf0  - The brush is slime.\plain\f2\fs20\cf0\b 
\par 
\par \tab Water\plain\f2\fs20\cf0  - The brush is water.\plain\f2\fs20\cf0\b 
\par 
\par \tab Mist\plain\f2\fs20\cf0  - The brush can be walked through.\plain\f2\fs20\cf0\b 
\par 
\par \tab AreaPortal\plain\f2\fs20\cf0  - The brush will block VIS. Refer to your level editor manual.\plain\f2\fs20\cf0\b 
\par 
\par \tab PlayerClip\plain\f2\fs20\cf0  - The player cannot walk through the brush, but other things can.\plain\f2\fs20\cf0\b 
\par 
\par \tab MonsterClip \plain\f2\fs20\cf0 - Monsters cannot walk through the brush, but other things can.\plain\f2\fs20\cf0\b 
\par 
\par \tab Current 0/90/180/270/up/dn\plain\f2\fs20\cf0  - Use with 'flowing' surface property to set the direction of flow.\plain\f2\fs20\cf0\b 
\par 
\par \tab Origin\plain\f2\fs20\cf0  - Sets the brush to be an origin. Refer to your level editor manual.\plain\f2\fs20\cf0\b 
\par 
\par \tab Detail\plain\f2\fs20\cf0  - The brush will not be included in the VIS process. Refer to your level editor manual.\plain\f2\fs20\cf0\b 
\par 
\par \tab Translucent\plain\f2\fs20\cf0  - The brush allows light to pass through it.\plain\f2\fs20\cf0\b 
\par 
\par \tab Ladder\plain\f2\fs20\cf0  - The brush is a ladder.
\par 
\par Most level editor manuals will go into far more detail about the surface attributes - this is intended as a basic guide, since it is more a level editing matter than a texture matter. You do not need to set these attributes in order to use them in your levels, as any settings in the map will override the flags in the .wal file - it is simply more convenient to have the flags already set when you build your level.\plain\f2\fs20 

