\deflang2057\pard\qc\plain\f2\fs32\cf0\b 
\par Creating a New Texture with Wally\plain\f2\fs32\cf3\b 
\par \pard\plain\f2\fs20\cf0 
\par \plain\f2\fs20 \tab This is a relatively simple procedure, requiring very little technical expertise; if done correctly, you can produce great-looking results. There are two ways to do it: the quicker way is to draw everything within Wally, and the slower, but better, way is to import an image or photograph from another paint app and use Wally to convert it to a Quake2 texture. For this tutorial, which will show you how to create a cliff texture from a photograph, we will take the longer route. It is assumed that you are capable of basic use of your paint app.
\par 
\par \tab 1. Find the photo you want to use (or take it, if you have a digital camera, you flashy show-off, you :) and load it into your paint app. Make sure that both dimensions are multiples of 16 (16, 32, 48, 64, 80 etc...), or Wally will not load it - Quake2 requires that ALL textures are divisible by 16 in both dimensions. Save it as a 24-bit .bmp image.
\par 
\par \tab 2. Start Wally, and click on the Convert Image button - \plain\f2\fs20\cf2 \{bmc convert.bmp\}\plain\f2\fs20 . Use the file selection dialogue to find and open your bmp file. Wally will load the image and convert it to the Quake2 palette, and create the three sub-mips. Click the ReMip button - \plain\f2\fs20\cf2 \{bmc remip.bmp\}\plain\f2\fs20  - to resample the image and create the sub-mip images.
\par 
\par \tab 3. Your texture should now look something like this:
